¶Introduction My recent essays, writing from mid-2025, are being described as difficult. Some describe them as impenetrable or alienating. Others say they are overcompressed, self-referential, or withholding. The most consistent descriptor is affective: it feels tiring—like a demand on the reader made without sufficient payoff. One reader described reading my recent writing as &amp;ldquo;running through wet cement, but I can&amp;rsquo;t stop.&amp;rdquo;
These assessments are accurate descriptions of what the essays are doing, rhetorically and structurally. What is wrong is the perception that it is anything but intentional. My recent essays are not designed to instruct, persuade, or resolve. They are not written for argument or clarity. They emerge from a specific configuration of constraints: energetic, economic, relational, cognitive, and systemic, primarily intersecting at two points:
